### ⚠️ Working but quality-limited

7. **DA3 backprojection bake** (`bake.py`) — produces a structurally-valid
   3DGS PLY (format byte-perfect, validated, loads in PlayCanvas without
   error), but **the splat renders BLACK in the SuperSplat Viewer**.
   See "What's broken" below.

### ❌ Known broken

8. **DA3-backprojected splat rendering.** PlayCanvas WebGPU GSplat
   rasterizer renders our DA3 PLY as **fully black** or **dark silhouette**.
   The rest of the SuperSplat Viewer chrome (UI, annotation cycler,
   timeline, camera controls) works.

## Root-cause analysis of the black-render

**The PLY is valid** — verified through the PlayCanvas parser path, byte
distribution, finite values, normalized quaternions, sane f_dc/scale/opacity
ranges (avg RGB linear (0.31, 0.35, 0.41), opacity sigmoid 0.99, scale
8-72 mm depending on tuning).

**The engine works** — the same scene/camera config that renders the
DA3 PLY as black renders the test-cube PLY as a vibrant rainbow.

**Decisive bisect test** — a hybrid PLY using **livedemo positions** but
**uniform pure white 10 cm opaque gaussians** renders as a **dark silhouette
that matches the splat's outline**. So the position cloud is being read,
the renderer IS iterating those splats, and they are producing output —
but the cumulative tile composition zeros out.

### The real reason

DA3-backprojected gaussians live on a **sampled 2.5 D depth manifold**.
Every pixel of every input view becomes one gaussian at its depth. Adjacent
pixels (same view, neighboring stride) lie on a near-coplanar tangent
patch. Multiple views see roughly the same surface and stack additional
co-planar layers behind it.

PlayCanvas's WebGPU GSplat compositor sorts and front-to-back blends per
screen tile. With many high-opacity co-planar gaussians, the cumulative
**transmittance underflows to ~0 after the first few layers**, and the
contribution of all subsequent (visible) gaussians becomes zero. The
rasterizer is mathematically correct — the data is the failure mode.

This is **NOT** an issue with:

- PLY format ✓
- Coordinate convention ✓ (OpenCV→PlayCanvas Y/Z flip in bake.py is right)
- Camera position / target / FOV ✓ (test cube renders fine at same camera)
- COOP/COEP cross-origin isolation ✓
- WebGPU SharedArrayBuffer availability ✓
- Canvas resize race ✓ (rAF-deferred fix landed in viewer source)
- Tonemapping / gamma / postFX ✓ (tested with tonemap=none)
- Gaussian scale (tested 8 mm — 30 cm — same result)
- Gaussian count (tested 1.7 k — 105 k — same result)
- Opacity (tested 0.15 — 0.99 — same result)

### The proper fix — k-NN init (TODO next session)

Real 3DGS trainers (Inria, gsplat, Brush) initialize gaussian scale per
point as the **average distance to the K=3 nearest neighbors**, and they
randomize per-point scale slightly to break perfect coplanarity. They also
write `f_rest_*` SH bands ≥ 1 so view-dependent shading prevents pure
co-planar saturation.

The bake.py change needed:

```python
from sklearn.neighbors import NearestNeighbors
nbrs = NearestNeighbors(n_neighbors=4).fit(xyz_all)
d, _ = nbrs.kneighbors(xyz_all)
local_scale = d[:, 1:].mean(axis=1)              # avg K=3 neighbor distance
jitter = np.random.uniform(0.7, 1.3, size=local_scale.shape)
scale = local_scale * jitter * 0.6                # ~3σ overlap between nbrs
```

Plus optionally write SH bands ≥ 1 (extra 9 f_rest_* properties) to give
the rasterizer view-dependent terms that break degenerate coplanar
composition.

Alternative: drive the PLY through one short pass of **gsplat training**
(which we already have in the splat-lab container) to refine positions
and scales away from the depth-manifold. ~1 minute of training is enough
to break the coplanarity in practice.

## Architecture as it stands

```
                ┌──────────── ON THE JETSON ──────────────┐
                │                                           │
[C615 USB] ─▶  │ live_stream.py daemon :8092               │
                │   • C615 → cv2 → YOLO11n TRT FP16         │
                │   • DAv2 Small ONNX/CUDA → INFERNO depth  │
                │   • tegrastats poller (RAM/GPU/W)         │
                │   • /stream /depth /detections /health    │
                │                                           │
                │ capture.py (one-shot)                     │
                │   • v4l2 lockdown + GStreamer MJPEG       │
                │   • YOLO11n score gate                    │
                │   • frames/ + detections.jsonl            │
                │                                           │
                │ bake.py (splat-lab container)             │
                │   • DA3-SMALL (PyTorch+CUDA, FP16 autocast)│
                │   • backproject → 3DGS PLY (Y-up flip)    │
                │   • settings.json with cameras[0].initial │
                │   • atomic tmpfile + rename               │
                │                                           │
                │ annotate.py (host venv)                   │
                │   • YOLO bboxes → DA3 extrinsics → world  │
                │   • pure-numpy DBSCAN (~40 LOC)           │
                │   • SuperSplat v2 settings annotations[]  │
                │                                           │
                │ nginx :8090 (HTTP) + :8443 (HTTPS)        │
                │   • COOP/COEP/CORP isolation triple       │
                │   • /live/* proxied to :8092              │
                │   • /<scan>/  static walkthrough          │
                │   • self-signed cert for LAN HTTPS        │
                └───────────────────────────────────────────┘
                          │
                          ▼
[Windows Chrome] ─SSH tunnel localhost:8090─▶ Jetson
                          │
                          ▼  http://localhost:8090/
                Live dashboard with everything ✓
```

## Numbers (measured this session)

### Concurrent live processing on Orin Nano 8GB
- RGB+YOLO stream: 6.7 FPS  →  YOLO11n TRT FP16 at ~34 ms inference
- DAv2 depth stream: 6.7 FPS  →  DAv2-Small at ~143 ms inference
- Both running together: **RAM 4.27/7.62 GB · GPU 95% · CPU 28% · 16.2 W**
- nginx + ssh-tunnel + per-stream overhead: negligible

### DA3 (run separately during bake)
- Cold load (HF download): 17.9 s
- Warm load: 1.4 s
- Idle VRAM: 138 MB
- Single 504² inference: 250 ms median, 278 MB peak
- 4-view multi-view: 1.50 s, 531 MB peak
- 6-view multi-view: 1.75 s, 702 MB peak
- 8-view: OOM — do not exceed 6 with current config

### End-to-end snap (`launcher.sh`)
- 30 s capture: ~32 s wall-clock (capture + select)
- 4-view bake: ~5 s
- Annotate: <0.5 s
- **Total: ~38 s from press-record to PLY on disk**
  (Browser walkthrough quality currently blocked by the k-NN fix)

